<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-472-497  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 472 497.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Sept 25 1990 v4 n32 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Working Mother magazine lauds Apple in annual company review.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pfiffner, Pamela.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (reports).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (usage).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersSurveyUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Pamela PfiffnerandM;New York -- For the fifth year in a row, Apple has been named one of the bestcompanies for working mothers.andP;  But other Silicon Valley companies faredpoorly in Working Mother magazine's annual review of businesses.andM;The survey, conducted by authors Milton Moskowitz and Carol Townsend andpublished in the New York-based monthly's October issue, recognized 75companies nationwide on the basis of pay, advancement opportunities, childcare and benefits.andM;Apple and rival IBM Corp. of Armonk, N.Y., made the top 10, while OracleCorp. of Redwood Shores, Calif., cracked the top 75 for the first time.andO;Digital Equipment Corp. of Maynard, Mass., also made the list.andO;Hewlett-Packard Co., in the top 60 last year, did not appear on the 1990list.andM;Apple took top honors in pay and child care and scored four out of a possiblefive in benefits.andP;  However, the company got only three out of five in careeradvancement.andM;Of Apple's 5,400 female employees -- less than half of the company's 12,000employees -- 33 percent are managers.andP;  Only two of Apple's 35 vice presidentsare women.andP;  Flex time is offered, while 179 female employees work part time,the survey said.andM;Apple's &quot;state-of-the-art&quot; child-care center has a staff 29 to watch over 70children and supplies six on-site computers.andP;  Unlike the new Macs, Apple'schild-care service isn't low-cost, however; the center costs working moms upto $166 per week.andP;  The company does, however, give $500 to new babies and$3,000 in aid to adoptive parents.andM;Newcomer Oracle also ranked tops in pay but scored three out of five in theother three categories.andP;  The software company is planning a child-care centerfor 1991.andP;  Oracle's maternity-leave policy is notable: New mothers receiveeight weeks paid leave, another eight with partial pay and up to one yearunpaid leave.andP;  In contrast, Apple grants six months of unpaid leave.andM;Working Mother has published the survey since 1986.andP;  The authors point outthat, according to the Department of Labor, mothers of children under 6 madeup 12 percent of the work force in 1950 compared with 56 percent today.andP;  Thatnumber will only continue to rise, they said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>